item.dc:creator: @Cheese_Police c|p
item.description:
@Cheese_Police wrote:

[quote=“BAsh, post:96, topic:261449”][quote author=Cheese_Police link=topic=345250.msg2677845#msg2677845 date=1235182912]
im writing it in clojure, so far so good (i think)

here, i pasted the relevant code, if you would like a look
[/quote]
I fail to understand how that code is a heuristical updater.

clojure is an interesting language but to me its a bit ugly and hard to understand.[/quote]

it isnt entirely heuristical, im playing around with examining class hierarchy, and will eventually examine other things as well, in order to define certain classes.

the node candidate is determined by looking for classes that have 5 parents. the only 2 occurances are the superclass of client, and some other class. following up the trail of parents of this class, node is the one directly before Object:

java.lang.Object - 0 ... re - 1 ... ta - 2 ... dh - 3 nf - 4 eh - 5

now, since the client changes every update, this is just a good guess as to where to look.
in the event the heuristic is wrong, no harm is done and the node transformer can be run in a more “traditional” fashion.

anyway, for now, its just fun and games, and learning how to use clojure effectively.

i know my code looks ugly, and it can probably be improved in a few ways.
however, the ugly and “hard to understand” comments you made are probably referring to the language itself, and i can see that.
i had a hard time (and still dont have an easy time) deciphering clojure (well, any lisp really), but now since i took the leap into learning it, its actually very easy to read and straightforward.
